<methodology slug="mom-test">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>comms</group>
    <domain>communicator</domain>
    <summary>Interview protocol to distinguish genuine problem signals from polite compliments: talk about their life, ask about past behavior, and listen more than pitch.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>mom-test</tag>
      <tag>customer-discovery</tag>
      <tag>validation</tag>
      <tag>interviews</tag>
      <tag>product-research</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-29</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>The Mom Test: Customer Discovery Interview Protocol</title>
    <summary>The Mom Test (Rob Fitzpatrick, 2013) is a customer discovery interview protocol with three rules: talk about their life not your idea; ask about past specifics not future hypotheticals; talk less than 20% of the time. It distinguishes genuine problem signals (specific past behavior, current spending, commitments) from worthless compliments ("sounds cool", "I would use this"). Real validation requires commitment — time (beta test), reputation (referral), or money (deposit) — not verbal enthusiasm.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>People lie politely when asked about your idea. They want to be kind, not honest. Future-hypothetical questions ("would you use this?") produce answers based on what they wish they were doing, not what they actually do. Past-behavior questions ("tell me about the last time you dealt with this problem") produce facts. Compliments feel like validation but predict zero buying behavior; commitments predict real behavior.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Early customer discovery before any code is written — validating that a problem is real and frequent.</item>
        <item>Screening interview transcripts to identify genuine signals vs polite noise.</item>
        <item>Generating interview question scripts that avoid leading, future-hypothetical, or opinion-seeking phrasing.</item>
        <item>Extracting commitment signals (time, money, referrals) from existing interview notes or CRM records.</item>
        <item>After 5+ interviews, running a synthesis pass to surface repeated patterns.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Post-launch product analytics — Mom Test is a discovery tool, not a measurement tool.</item>
        <item>B2B enterprise procurement where formal RFPs are required — conversational style reads as unprepared.</item>
        <item>Quantitative surveys — explicitly qualitative, single-subject methodology.</item>
        <item>When you already have paying customers with observable behavior; switch to churn/retention analysis.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="three-rules">
      <p>Three core rules eliminate the politeness bias that makes most customer interviews worthless. The rules prevent you from pitching, leading, and asking hypotheticals.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Rule 1: Ask about their life and problems, not about your idea or solution. Never mention your idea until you have established whether the problem is real.</statement>
        <rationale>When you mention your idea, the interview becomes an evaluation of you, not a discovery of their needs. Polite respondents optimize for not hurting your feelings.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Rule 2: Ask about past specific behavior, not future hypotheticals. "Would you..." and "Do you think..." produce answers based on what people wish they did, not what they actually do.</statement>
        <rationale>Past behavior is the best predictor of future behavior. Hypothetical behavior reflects self-concept, which routinely diverges from actual behavior.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Rule 3: Listen more than 80% of the time. If you are talking more than 20% of the time, you are pitching, not learning.</statement>
        <rationale>Pitching during discovery contaminates the data — the interviewee starts responding to your framing instead of describing their actual experience.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="good-vs-bad-questions">
      <p>The three rules translate into specific question patterns. Bad questions cluster around opinions, futures, and leading assumptions. Good questions cluster around past behavior and specifics.</p>
      <list>
        <item>Bad: "Do you think this is a good idea?" → Good: "How do you currently solve this?"</item>
        <item>Bad: "Would you buy this?" → Good: "When did you last pay for a solution to this problem?"</item>
        <item>Bad: "Would you use this feature?" → Good: "Tell me about the last time you had this problem"</item>
        <item>Bad: "How much would you pay?" → Good: "What do you currently spend on this?"</item>
        <item>Bad: "Do you have this problem?" (leading) → Good: "Walk me through your workflow"</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="commitment-escalation-ladder">
      <p>Real validation requires escalating commitment from the interviewee. Verbal enthusiasm is costless and therefore worthless. Commitment in time, reputation, or money reflects genuine belief.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Real validation requires escalating commitment: Time commitment (beta test agreement) is the minimum bar; Reputation commitment (introduction to a colleague or CTO) is stronger; Money commitment (deposit, prepayment, pilot contract) is the strongest signal.</statement>
        <rationale>Verbal enthusiasm is costless and therefore uninformative. Commitment costs the interviewee something real, so it reflects genuine belief in the value.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Compliment (worthless): "I would definitely use this", "Great idea!", "Interesting concept"</item>
        <item>Time (minimum): "Can I be a beta tester?", "Schedule a pilot next month"</item>
        <item>Reputation: "I'll introduce you to our CTO", "I'll send you our requirements doc"</item>
        <item>Money (strongest): "$50 deposit", "We'll sign an LOI", "I'll prepay for the first year"</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="red-flags-in-interview-answers">
      <p>Certain phrases and patterns in interview answers indicate weak or contaminated data. These are signals to probe deeper or discard the statement.</p>
      <list>
        <item>"I would..." — hypothetical, not real; probe for a specific past instance.</item>
        <item>"I usually..." — generic pattern; probe for the last specific time.</item>
        <item>"I think..." — opinion, not behavior; ask for a concrete example.</item>
        <item>Compliments without follow-up questions from them — signals low interest.</item>
        <item>Vague answers — signals they have not actually experienced the problem.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="interview-structure">
      <p>A Mom Test interview follows four phases: Opening (neutral context), Exploration (specific past behavior), Digging (depth and cost), and Closing (referrals). The structure ensures uncontaminated behavioral data throughout.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Open with a neutral topic (their work context), explore specific past behavior, dig into cost and workarounds, then close by asking for referrals. Do not mention your idea until after the exploration phase — if at all.</statement>
        <rationale>Opening with your idea frames all subsequent questions as evaluation of your solution. Opening with their context produces uncontaminated behavioral data.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Opening (2 min): "I'm trying to understand how people deal with [GENERAL AREA]. Tell me about your experience with [TOPIC]."</item>
        <item>Exploration (15 min): "Walk me through the last time you [DID THING]", "What was hardest about that?", "How did you solve it?", "What else have you tried?"</item>
        <item>Digging (5 min): "Why is that important?", "Can you give me a specific example?", "How much time/money does this cost you?"</item>
        <item>Closing (3 min): "Who else should I talk to about this?", "What should I have asked that I didn't?"</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="data-categories-to-collect">
      <p>Every interview should collect signals across five key categories. Missing any category leaves gaps in validating whether a real market exists.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Collect five categories of signal in every interview: Problem (does it exist, frequency, severity), Current solution (what they already use and why), Willingness to pay (have they paid for solutions before), Decision process (who decides, timeline, criteria), Urgency (active vs passive searching).</statement>
        <rationale>Missing any category leaves gaps in the problem hypothesis. Decision process is the most commonly skipped and most important for B2B sales.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="post-interview-processing">
      <p>How interview data is processed after the conversation matters as much as the conversation itself. Exact quotes and pattern cross-referencing prevent analyst bias and hallucination.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Immediately after the interview, record exact quotes (not paraphrases). Rate each signal as Strong / Weak / No signal. After 5+ interviews, run a cross-transcript synthesis pass looking for repeated problems (3+ independent mentions).</statement>
        <rationale>Paraphrasing introduces analyst bias into the data. Exact quotes preserve the specific words and dollar amounts that are the highest-value signals. Pattern recognition requires 3+ independent mentions to be credible.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Never let an agent score "problem severity" on a 1-10 scale from text alone. Require minimum quote count per pattern (3+ independent mentions from separate interviewees) before treating a pattern as validated.</statement>
        <rationale>Agents produce confident-sounding severity scores from thin data. A severity of "8/10" from one interview is not a validated problem.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="agent-integration-guidelines">
      <p>Agents can assist with Mom Test question generation and transcript analysis, but cannot replace the human conducting the interview or validating patterns across transcripts.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>When using agents for question generation: provide a problem hypothesis and request 10+ Mom Test-compliant questions. Rules must be enforced: no opinion questions, no future hypotheticals, no leading questions. Review wording against the three Mom Test rules before use.</statement>
        <rationale>Agents generate compliant-looking questions that are still subtly leading. Human review is essential because leading questions produce contaminated data even when they appear neutral.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>When using agents for transcript analysis: classify each statement as Problem Signal / Current Solution Signal / Commitment Signal / Compliment (discard) / Red Flag (hypothetical). Require minimum quote count (3+ independent mentions) before surfacing a pattern. Never allow the agent to score problem severity without explicit quote evidence.</statement>
        <rationale>Agents summarize away the specific words and dollar amounts that are the most valuable signals. Enforcing quote evidence and cross-referencing prevents hallucinated patterns.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Run question generation pass before each interview batch, not once at project start. Adapt based on what previous interviews revealed. Update the "problem hypothesis" document after every 5 interviews.</statement>
        <rationale>Discovery is iterative. Early questions target the hypothesis; later questions test refinements. Static question sets become increasingly misaligned as understanding evolves.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>LLMs will generate compliant-looking questions that are still subtly leading. Review wording against the three Mom Test rules before use.</item>
        <item>Transcript summarization almost always loses nuance — agents tend to summarize away the specific words and dollar amounts that are the most valuable signals.</item>
        <item>An agent asked to "find patterns across 5 interviews" will hallucinate consensus if the transcripts are thin; require minimum quote count per pattern (e.g., 3+ independent mentions).</item>
        <item>Human checkpoint required: the agent cannot distinguish genuine enthusiasm from rehearsed politeness in text transcripts without tone markers.</item>
        <item>Track the commitment escalation ladder per interviewee: Time → Reputation → Money. Anyone who only gives verbal compliments should be weighted near zero.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
